In a recent press briefing, Acting Administrator Slavitt, along with Drs. Walensky and Fauci, discussed the rise in COVID-19 cases in the United States. They emphasized the need to continue following public health guidelines, such as wearing masks, practicing social distancing, and getting vaccinated. They reported that the country is making progress in vaccination efforts, with an average of 2.7 million vaccinations per week and a total of 50 million fully vaccinated Americans. They also announced the opening of two new federally run mass vaccination sites in St. Louis, Missouri, and Gary, Indiana. Dr. Walensky expressed her concerns about the recent increase in cases and urged people to remain cautious, highlighting the importance of vaccination in preventing infections. Dr. Fauci shared data on the severity of COVID-19 and the effectiveness of vaccines in preventing hospitalizations and deaths. The officials also addressed questions about the government's role in vaccination passports, travel guidelines, and the distribution of Johnson & Johnson vaccines. They emphasized the need for equitable access to vaccines, privacy of information, and a marketplace of solutions for vaccination passports. They acknowledged the concerns of the public and stated that the government is working with the private sector on this issue.